<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[831,1437,594,1837]" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schonherr" authorityYear="1823" box="[876,987,594,617]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Apionidae</taxonomicName>
group is only weakly (NJ) or insufficiently (ML &lt;50%) supported in our analyses (
<figureCitation box="[1266,1330,626,651]" captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,186,1908,1929]" captionTargetBox="[155,1408,263,1896]" captionTargetId="graphics@3.[544,992,642,2095]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Best Maximum Likelihood tree as selected by MEGA) based on COI sequences of 142 samples of Curculionoidea (Chrysomelidae obtained by using MEGA 6. Values (over 50 %) of bootstrap support from 100 nodes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1040870/files/figure.svg" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, Supp. 1) but, on the contrary, the monophyly of the genera (i. e. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alonso-Zarazaga" authorityYear="1990" box="[831,923,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Aizobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[831,923,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">Aizobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[940,1115,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Voss" authorityYear="1859" box="[940,1112,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hemitrichapion</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alonso-Zarazaga" authorityYear="1990" box="[1174,1279,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Osellaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1174,1279,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">Osellaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) found strong support in both the ML and NJ tree.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[831,1437,594,1837]" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alonso-Zarazaga" authorityYear="1990" box="[958,1063,755,778]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Osellaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[958,1063,755,778]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">Osellaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is represented with three strictly subalpine-alpine taxa in the western alpine arch – 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bello, Meregalli &amp; Osella, 1980)" authorityName="Bello, Meregalli &amp; Osella" authorityYear="1980" baseAuthorityName="Bello, Meregalli &amp; Osella" baseAuthorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Osellaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="bonvouloirii" subSpecies="baldensis">
<emphasis box="[831,1115,819,843]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">O. bonvouloirii baldensis</emphasis>
(Bellò, Meregalli &amp; Osella, 1980)
</taxonomicName>
on Monte Baldo, 
<taxonomicName authority="Christoph Germann &amp; Sofia Wyler &amp; Marco Valerio Bernasconi, 2017" authorityName="Christoph Germann &amp; Sofia Wyler &amp; Marco Valerio Bernasconi" authorityYear="2017" box="[1077,1239,851,875]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Osellaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" sensu="stricto" species="bonvouloirii" status="s. str.">
<emphasis box="[1077,1239,851,875]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">O. bonvouloirii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1243,1297,852,875]" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Ch. Brisout, 1880) in the central and western Alps and 
<taxonomicName authority="Germann, 2010" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Osellaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="bonvouloirii" subSpecies="occidentalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">O. bonvouloirii occidentalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C." box="[968,1135,916,940]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" pagination="41 - 118" part="83" refString="Germann C. 2010 a. Die Russelkafer der Schweiz - Checkliste (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea) mit Verbreitungsangaben nach biogeografischen Regionen. Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 83: 41 - 118." title="Die Russelkafer der Schweiz - Checkliste (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea) mit Verbreitungsangaben nach biogeografischen Regionen" type="journal article" year="2010">Germann, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the Vercors (
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C. &amp; Szallies A." journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" pagination="171 - 180" part="84" refString="Germann C., Szallies A. 2011. Osellaeus bonvouloirii (Ch. Brisout, 1880) - a summary of its references, distribution and new insights into biology and phenology (Coleoptera, Apionidae). Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 84: 171 - 180." title="Osellaeus bonvouloirii (Ch. Brisout, 1880) - a summary of its references, distribution and new insights into biology and phenology (Coleoptera, Apionidae)" type="journal article" year="2011">Germann &amp; Szallies, 2011</bibRefCitation>
). We included three Swiss populations of the nominal subspecies, but the third one from the Valais did not produce a positive PCR. The one from Uri (Brisen) and the other from Fribourg (Kaiseregg) are from localities just 91 km distant from each other. As 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Christoph Germann &amp; Sofia Wyler &amp; Marco Valerio Bernasconi" authorityYear="2017" box="[872,1042,1108,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Osellaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bonvouloirii">
<emphasis box="[872,1042,1108,1132]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">O. bonvouloirii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a flightless, and restricted to its alpine habitat and thus a very low mobile species, the detected differences (K2 distance: 0.059; 
<tableCitation box="[1299,1382,1172,1197]" captionStart="Tables 1 - 8" captionStartId="11.[151,213,258,279]" captionText="Tables 1 - 8: COI Kimura 2 - Parameter genetic distances for a set of selected samples used in the present study. See the main text for further details." pageId="2" pageNumber="17">Table 1</tableCitation>
) are well explainable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[831,1437,594,1837]" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
Three other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schonherr" authorityYear="1823" box="[994,1105,1236,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Apionidae</taxonomicName>
were included, of which 
<emphasis box="[832,1140,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName box="[832,1001,1268,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Mesotrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesotrichapion</taxonomicName>
punctirostre
</emphasis>
(Gyllenhal, 1839) did not give a result. The species with the widest distribution reaching from Central Asia to France is 
<emphasis box="[1290,1436,1332,1355]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alonso-Zarazaga" authorityYear="1990" box="[1290,1382,1332,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Aizobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Aizobius</taxonomicName>
sedi
</emphasis>
(Germar, 1818). However, the species is restricted to xerothermic places and unable to fly, this may explain for the rather large intraspecific genetic distance (0.027) between the two samples taken 300 km from each other. The third species sampled is 
<emphasis box="[1174,1436,1493,1516]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Voss" authorityYear="1859" box="[1174,1343,1493,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hemitrichapion</taxonomicName>
waltoni
</emphasis>
(Stephens, 1839), recorded from Hungaria to France. The samples taken at localities separated by a distance of 340 km, a species which has normally developed hind wings and is the most mobile of all species included and may therefore show the lowest genetic distance of all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schonherr" authorityYear="1823" box="[831,942,1685,1708]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Apionidae</taxonomicName>
included (0.011).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[831,1437,594,1837]" pageId="2" pageNumber="17">These results underline once more the importance of the need for conservation of isolated populations of flightless, ecologically highly specialised and thus low mobile endemic species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
